passages.text: 2Q25 results were mixed as sales were in- line, with comps of \(+1.0\%\) missing consensus of \(+1.7\%\) GM missed by 70bps, while beating on OM and EPS, as a technology related expenses shifted from 2Q25 to 3Q25. FY25 sales guidance was reaffirmed but OM was lowered due to incremental tariff pressure.

As Gap Gets its Groove Back, Tariffs Pressure Margins. GAP drove solid 2Q25 results driven by Old Navy, Gap, and Banana Republic, offset by Athleta. Gap's "Better in Denim" campaign showed the resurgence of the Gap brand to its heritage roots. As Gap finds its momentum for a broad- based turnaround, tariffs remain a current and looming overhang on margins. While we believe in management's turnaround strategy, we recently downgraded shares of GAP to Equal Weight (Blue- Sky Upside Scenario Off the Table; Downgrade to Equal Weight - 22 Aug '25) ahead of its earnings. We believe our previous blue- sky scenario for significant margin and upward EPS revisions driving towards a \(- 10\%\) OM by FY26 is off the table, diminished by tariff margin pressure and macro uncertainty, materializing in 2H25 and FY25 guidance. However, on the positive side, the company does not currently expect the annualization of tariffs in 2026 to cause further operating income declines in FY26, and it expects to mitigate the full impact of tariffs over time. In addition, the company cited that without the negative tariff impacts it would have expanded both GM and OM in- line with its original expectations. Related to the quarter, we are encouraged by GAP's ability to continue to deliver positive comps and in particular the \(+4\%\) comp growth at the Gap brand as the company continues to execute on its playbook through a wide assortment of elevated product offerings, trend- right products, and compelling marketing campaigns, leading to an increase in customer engagement, driving higher AUR and spend per customer. The company also saw strength at ON and BR, though this was partially offset by the Athleta brand, which remains challenged. However, despite making progress on its reset strategies, we remain on the sidelines as we believe the reset actions will take more time, and we advise waiting for a better entry point to reestablish positions in shares of GAP once sustainable margin expansion is more visible. In reaction on 8/28/25 in the aftermarket, GAP shares traded - 2.7% versus the S&P 500 flat.

Risk factors to EW. Upside risks to our EW rating include the following: 1) sustainable positive comps at Old Navy, Gap, and BR; 2) opportunity to reduce and optimize SG&A; and 3) already- cautious sentiment surrounding sector- wide tariff impact. Downside risks to our EW rating

Tariff exposure update. Management guided to a net tariff impact of \(\) 150\(mn to\) \ \(175m n\) (prior \(\) 100m n\(to\) \ \(150m n\) in FY25, representing 100bps to 110bps of operating margin pressure. 3Q25 gross margin is projected to deleverage by 150bps to 170bps, which includes approx. 200bps from tariffs. FY25 gross margin is projected to deleverage by 70bps to 90bps, which includes approx. 100bps to 110bps from tariffs. However, the company does not anticipate incremental operating income declines in FY26 and believes it can offset the full impact over time. Mitigation measures include sourcing and manufacturing adjustments, targeted pricing actions, and assortment changes.

Quarter in review. Adj. EPS of \(\) 0.57\(came in ahead of consensus of\) \ \(0.55\) driven by SG&A leverage, partially offset lower GM. Comp sales of \(+1.0\%\) missed consensus of \(+1.7\%\) , with core Gap \(+4.0\%\) , Banana Republic \(+4.0\%\) , and Old Navy \(+2.0\%\) , partially offset by Athleta - \(9.0\%\) . Gross margin of \(41.2\%\) missed (vs. consensus of \(41.9\%\) ) as merchandise margin decreased - 150bps (though 80bps - 90bps was related to lapping the credit card benefit in 2Q24), partially offset by ROD leverage of \(+10\) bps. SG&A rate of \(33.4\%\) of sales beat (vs. cons. of \(34.4\%\) ) due to a shift in timing of technology related expenses into 3Q25. Management updated its FY25 guidance including net sales up \(+1.0\%\) to \(+2.0\%\) (unchanged from prior and vs. cons. \(+1.6\%\) ), GM down 70bps to 90bps (from prior expand slightly ex- tariffs and vs. cons. - 60bps or \(40.7\%\) ), OpEx to leverage slightly (unchanged from prior and vs. cons. - 40bps or \(33.5\%\) ), OM in the range of \(6.7\%\) to \(7.0\%\) (vs. cons. \(7.1\%\) ), tax rate of \(27.0\%\) (from prior \(26.0\%\) ), and CapEx of \(\) 500m\(tn to\) \ \(550m n\) (from prior \(\) 600m n\(). Guidance for 3Q25 includes net sales up \(+1.5\%\) to \(+2.5\%\) (vs. cons. \(+2.1\%\) ), GM down 150bps to 170bps (including 200bps of net tariff impact and vs. cons. - 110bps or \(41.6\%\) ), and OpEx % to deleverage slightly (vs. cons. - 20bps or \(33.2\%\) ).

Inventory. Based on our proprietary inventory analysis, GAP has posted three consecutive quarters of negative sales- to- inventory growth. In FY2Q25 the Inventory Management Spread ("IM Spread") was (804) basis points and worsened from (328) basis points in the prior quarter. GAP's Gross Margin Return on Inventory ("GMROI") has worsened for three consecutive quarters, and its Operating Margin Return on Inventory ("OMROI") has worsened for one quarter.

Lowering estimates and maintaining PT of \(\) 19\(. Our FY25, FY26, and FY27 adj. EPS estimates are\) \ \(2.05\) , \(\) 2.13\(, and\) \ \(2.35\) (from \(\) 2.10\(,\) \ \(2.14\) , and \(\) 2.43\(), respectively, due to slightly lower sales and SG&A deleverage. We maintain our PT of\) \ \(19\) , which is based on 8x (was 9x) applied to our CY27E adj. EPS of \(\) 2.35\(from CY26E adj. EPS of\) \ \(2.14\) . Our multiple is two turns below the current NTM P/E multiple is \(10.0x\) , as we roll forward our PT, which is now based on our CY27 EPS estimate vs. our prior CY26 estimate.

From a fundamental perspective, we use our proprietary PRISM cycle as a leading indicator of potential sales inflection (i.e., either from positive to negative or negative to positive). Our PRISM Curve attempts to look for fundamental changes in the business model of a company, driven by proactive management decisions to stabilize margins (e.g., purge inventory, cut costs, share best practices, invest in product and brand). Figure 2 and Figure 3 below depict our model graphically and identify where we would theoretically expect to see sales and margin changes along the business model curve.

We believe GAP has transitioned from the HUNT phase to the CHASE phase across the consolidated business. During the CHASE phase, management's strategy is more on the defense as new entrants encroach on their dominant position and increase the intensity of the competitive backdrop. As the company moves further through Region C in the HUNT phase, eventually it begins to face year- over- year compares that may be too difficult for it to anniversary or new competitors make market share gains more challenging. At this point, a company will pass the point of comp acceleration, and its comps will begin to decelerate, as seen in Region F as it enters the CHASE phase. Here comps are still positive, but less so, and the company is no longer able to post the large comp and earnings surprises that it could in the past.

During the CHASE phase, management's strategy shifts more to defense as new entrants and competitors are "chasing" them, and they may be losing incremental share at the margin to those competitors. In Region F, however, the company can go in one of two distinct directions: it can either: 1) continue to slide into negative comps (and cross Point G), or 2) re- accelerate and catch a "second wind," effectively jumping back into Region C and back into the HUNT phase. Even if a company has passed its fundamental peak, we believe that valuation can be attractive and earnings can still accelerate through buybacks and cost reduction. However, increasing macro uncertainty may make a "second wind" scenario more difficult.

Tariff exposure update. Management guided to a net tariff impact of \(\) 150m\(to\) \ \(175m\) (prior \(\) 100m\(to\) \ \(150m\) ) in FY25, representing 100bps to 110bps of operating margin pressure. 3Q25, gross margin is projected to deleverage by 150bps to 170bps, which includes approx. 200bps from tariffs. However, the company does not anticipate incremental operating income declines in FY26 and believes it can offset the full impact over time. Mitigation measures include sourcing and manufacturing adjustments, targeted pricing actions, and assortment changes.

Prior tariff commentary. For FY25, the company expects tariffs to take a \(\sim 100\) bps bite out of OM. GAP did not embed current tariff rates into its reiterated full- year expectations, but if the current tariffs remain ( \(30\%\) on most imports from China and \(10\%\) on most imports from other countries), the company noted the gross incremental cost is projected at \(\) 250m\(- \\(300m\). However, the company has enacted and is working on various mitigation strategies, which it believes can offset more than half of the gross cost and sees the remaining net impact of about \(\) 100m\(to\) \ \(150m\) to FY25 operating income, primarily in 2H25. Its mitigation strategies include 1) diversifying its sourcing footprint and 2) nearshoring/domestic investment, such as doubling its vendor sourcing of American- grown cotton in 2025. Recall, GAP has been diversifying its sourcing footprint for several years, reducing exposure to its top sourcing country, China, to under \(10\%\) in 2024, with a goal of reducing it below \(3\%\) by 2025. Most other countries represent less than \(10\%\) of sourcing: Vietnam and Indonesia accounted for \(27\%\) and \(19\%\) last year, respectively. GAP plans to have no single country exceed \(25\%\) of its sourcing by the end of 2026.

Barclays Tariff "QuikCalc" Model assumptions. We update our Tariff "QuikCalc" model analysis, which now assumes global tariff assumptions effective 8/7/25. Our prior tariff analysis assumed \(30\%\) China and \(10\%\) Rest of World (excluding Mexico and Canada). Note our estimate of Tariff on Goods Imported to the US is a gross unmitigated amount for a full year, and we calculate the price increase necessary to mitigate full tariff cost (absent other mitigation strategies). Our updated tariff calculator under 8/7/25 effective rates suggests that for GAP total average unit cost will increase by \(15.6\%\) with pass- through to the US market only increasing prices by \(7.2\%\) (see Figure 12). The annual unmitigated margin impact increases to 632bps from 389bps under the 4/2/25 tariff scenario.
